{
  "doc_id": "8440",
  "text": "Clay-abundant shales mainly are constituted of quartz, clay minerals and TOC. According to research findings, the existence of significant amounts of small clay particles causes reduced tensile and shear strength values, because clay particles obstruct stress transmission through the contact between quartz particles [CITATION_1] . For this reason, clay-abundant shales mostly behave as ductile rock constituents with less brittleness [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The significant influence of clay particles on the mechanical There is also a negative effect of clay minerals on gas storage capacity due to their high affinity to water molecules, and greater clay content leads to greater water content in the shale play. For example, according to Ross and Bustin [CITATION_4] , the Gordondale member and Poker Chip shales have around 7.4% and 17-20% of aluminosilicate clay mineral fractions, and their moisture contents are around 0.6-8.5% and 5-11%, respectively. This greater moisture content offered by clay particles to the shale mass is not favourable for its gas storage capacity, because the available water molecules tend to occupy some potential sorption sites in the shale mass, blocking small pore throats. Both of these greatly reduce the gas adsorption capacity and eventually, the gas storage capacity. For example, Ross and Bustin [CITATION_5] found that a shale mass with equilibrium moisture content has up to around 40% less methane adsorption capacity than a dry shale mass. In addition, immobile water molecules occupy some pore space of the shale mass, reducing the pore space available for free gas [CITATION_6] . According to Godec et al. [CITATION_7] , the available effective porosity (Ø effective ) for free gas can be written as follows:",
